\b\fs28 CODE CONVENTIONS FOR DIFFERENT CATEGORIES:\par
1- File Names:\par
\b0\fs24 This section lists commonly used file suffixes and names.\par
\b  1.1 File Suffixes\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc File Type        Suffix\b0\par
Java source          .java\par
Java bytecode        .class\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b\fs28 2 - File Organization:\par
\b0\fs24 A file consists of sections that should be separated by blank lines and an optional comment identifying each section.\par
Files longer than 2000 lines are cumbersome and should be avoided.\par
\b  2.1 Java Source Files:\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1  \b0 When private classes and interfaces are associated with a public class, you can put them in the same source file as the public class. \par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}The public class should be the first class or interface in the file.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b\i Java source files have the following ordering:\par
\b0\i0 1.\f1  Beginning comments \par
\f0 2.\f1  Package and Import statements; for example:\par
\f0\tab\f1 import java.applet.Applet;\par
\f0\tab\f1 import java.awt.*;\par
\f0\tab\f1 import java.net.*;\par
\f0 3.\f1 Class and interface declarations \par
\b\f0 1.Beginning comments:\par
\b0 All source files should begin with a c-style comment that lists the programmer(s), the date, a copyright notice, and also a brief description of the purpose of the program. For example:\par
/*\par
 * Classname\par
*\par
 * Version info\par
 *\par
 * Copyright notice\par
 */\par
\b 2. Package and Import Statements:\par
\b0\lang9 The first non-comment line of most Java source files is a package statement. After that, import statements can follow. For example:\par
package java.awt;\par
import java.awt.peer.CanvasPeer;\par
\b 3. Class and Interface Declarations:\par
\b0 The following table describes the parts of a class or interface declaration, in the order that they should appear.\par
\b\i 1.Class/interface implementation comment (/*...*/), if necessary: \b0\i0 This comment should contain any class-wide or interface-wide information that wasn\rquote t appropriate for the class/interface documentation comment.\par
\b\i 2. Class (static) variables: \b0\i0 First the public class variables, then the protected, and then the private.\par
\b\i\lang1033 3.\f1\lang9  Methods\f0\lang1033 :\f1\lang9  \b0\i0 These methods should be grouped by functionality rather than by scope or accessibility. For\f0\lang1033  \f1\lang9 example, a private class method can be in\par
between two public instance methods. The goal is\par
to make reading and understanding the code easier\b\f0\par
\fs28 3.INDENTATION:\par
\i\fs24 Indentation: \b0\i0 Four spaces should be used as the unit of indentation. The exact construction of the indentation (spaces vs. tabs) is unspecified. Tabs must be set exactly every 8 spaces (not 4).\par
\b\i  3.1.Line Length:\par
\b0\i0 Avoid lines longer than 80 characters, since they\rquote re not handled well by many terminals and tools.\par
\b\i\f1  \f0\lang1033 3.2\f1\lang9  Wrapping Lines\f0\lang1033 :\f1\lang9\par
\b0\i0 When an expression will not fit on a single line, break it according to these general principles:\par
\bullet  Break after a comma.\par
\bullet  Break before an operator.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\f0\lang1033 (or)\f1\lang9\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\bullet  If the above rules lead to confusing code or to code that\rquote s squished up against the right\f0\lang1033  \f1\lang9 margin, just indent 8 spaces instead.\par
Here are some examples of breaking method calls:\par
\f0\lang1033 eg.1. \f1\lang9 function(longExpression1, longExpression2, longExpression3,\par
 longExpression4, longExpression5);\par
\f0\lang1033 eg2. \f1\lang9 var = function1(longExpression1,\par
 function2(longExpression2,\par
 longExpression3));\par
