\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b\f0\fs28\lang1033 5.COMMENTS:\b0\fs24\par
Java programs can have two kinds of comments,\par
1. implementation comments and\par
2.documentation comments.\par
\b\i Implementation comments:\b0\i0  \par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Implementation comments are those found in C++, which are delimited by /*...*/,\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}Implementation comments are mean for commenting out code or for comments about the particular implementation.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b\i Documentation comments:\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b0\i0  Documentation comments (known as \ldblquote doc comments\rdblquote ) are Java-only, and are delimited by /**...*/.\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}Doc comments are meant to describe the specification of the code, from an implementation-free perspective. to be read by developers who might not necessarily have the source code at hand.\b\i\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\i0\fs22  5.1 IMPLEMENTATION COMMENT FORMATS:\par
\b0\fs24 Programs can have four styles of implementation comments: \par
1.block comments, \par
2.single-line comments, \par
3.trailing comments and \par
4.end-of-line comments.\par
\b\i 1.Block Comments:\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1  \b0\i0 Block comments are used to provide descriptions of files, methods, data structures and algorithms. Block comments should be used at the beginning of each file and before each method.\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}A block comment should be preceded by a blank line to set it apart from the rest of the code\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 .\tab\tab\tab\tab /*\par
 \tab\tab\tab\tab * Here is a block comment.\par
 \tab\tab\tab\tab */\par
\b\i 2 Single-Line Comments:\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b0\i0 Short comments can appear on a single line indented to the level of the code that follows. \par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}If a comment can\rquote t be written in a single line, it should follow the block comment format.\b\i\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b0\i0                 if (condition) \{\par
   \tab\tab\tab   /* Handle the condition. */\par
 \tab\tab\tab\tab ...\par
\tab\tab\tab    \} \b\i\par
3 Trailing Comments:\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b0\i0 Very short comments can appear on the same line as the code they describe, but should be shifted far enough to separate them from the statements.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\tab\tab if (a == 2) \{\par
\tab  \tab return TRUE;\tab\tab  /* special case */\par
\tab\tab\} else \{\par
 \tab\tab return isprime(a); \tab /* works only for odd a */\par
\tab\tab\}\par
\b\i 4 End-Of-Line Comments:\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b0\i0 The // comment delimiter begins a comment that continues to the newline.\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab} It can comment out a complete line or only a partial line.\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab} It shouldn\rquote t be used on consecutive multiple lines for text comments; however, it can be used in consecutive multiple lines for commenting outsections of code. \b\i\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}\b0\i0  Examples of all three styles follow:\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\tab\tab if (foo > 1) \{\par
 \tab\tab\tab // Do a double-flip.\par
